Preheat your #oven{} to 210°C.

Peel and chop the @sweet potato{1} into 1cm chunks (no need to peel).

Pop the sweet potato onto a #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer. When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden and tender, ~{16-18%minutes}.

Halve, peel and chop the @red onion{1} into small pieces.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the @lime{1}.

Drain and rinse the @lentils{1%can} in a #sieve{}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} over medium-high heat. Once hot, add the @diced chicken breast{260%g} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook until browned all over, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Add the onion and cook, stirring, until softened, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add the garlic and @pasanda style seasoning{1}. Cook, stirring, ~{1%minute}.

Add the @coconut milk{200%ml}, @vegetable stock paste{10%g} and @water{50%ml} for the curry. Mix well, then add the lentils.

Bring to the boil, stir and lower the heat so the sauce simmers gently. Cook until the chicken is cooked through, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Add the @baby spinach{100%g} to the curry a handful at a time. Stir until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Once the sweet potato is cooked, add to the curry with a squeeze of lime juice. Taste and season if needed.

> TIP: Add a splash more water if it's a bit dry.

Cut any remaining lime into wedges.

Divide the lentil and chicken curry between your #bowls{}.

Serve with any remaining lime wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!

> MOD STEP 4: If you've added prawns to your curry, once the chicken is cooked, stir the @?king prawns{150%g} into the curry and cook for another ~{3-4%minutes}. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.